commentBody:
@jennie
Why have a paper copy of tax returns when they can be saved to the cloud?  I do have a printer but keep important papers in photo albums on my tablet/phone in the unlikely event they need to be printed out again. 

Nice quick solve. I enjoyed this one.

@Jeanne
Continued from prior post  (I hate the little comment window.)
A refurbished older printer is likely to last longer than a new cheapie. Find a cheap supplier of off-label toner; you don't need to pay Canon $23.95 for the pleasure of reading their label on the toner box. Print copies of your necessary stuff. Stash them somewhere safe.

@jennie 

I actually need to print anything once or twice a year, tops, and it's usually just a few pages. It makes much more sense to use the printer at work for that than have one of my own. I have never even looked at the buttons on that work HP - I just click "print" on the computer and voila.

All Polish tax returns are handled digitally.

@SBK in TO

I have a Brother INKvestment printer. The ink lasts almost forever.

I print out vintage acrostics from the NYT on it, among many other things. Like USPS labels to ship things I sell on ebay! Yay!

@Jeanne 

Whenever I hear "in the cloud," I mentally substitute "on somebody else's computer." 

Regardless of how much I'm assured that "cloud storage" is secure, the idea of storing my tax returns on somebody else's computer doesn't sit well with me. I know that the IRS has them, but I'd rather limit my exposure to that.

@dutchiris
I strongly support the serendipitous element of paper-based research. You never know when something above or below or on the opposite page will catch your eye and prove more interesting than your official destination 
And as for the internet: the ratio of worthwhile to garbage is tilting ever more trash-ward. I would much sooner trust a fellow puzzler than the unknown machine that assembled AbsolutelyTrueWordOrigins.com out of the garbage left here by other machines.

@MaryEllen
@Barry Ancona

We might add that people also come here to take part in a "virtual community" of people with "similar values".  It's more pleasant to ask a question of the community than to look it up for oneself.
IMO.

@MaryEllen
Don't forget the stacks.  They were still open to anyone with a librray card when I was there,  an experience like the Encyclopedia Britannica on the living room floor—all those books you might not have known existed. The UT Chief Reference Librarian was astounding. It seemed like she knew every book in the vast collection. Faculty members relied on her and she was acknowledged multiple times. 

I remember once a historian came into the office and said he was looking for books on X (don't remember the topic), and she got that drowsy, inward looking expression on her face and said, "Yeees, I saw a book about that on the fourth floor, it was green. I don't remember the title." She drifted out the door, and a few minutes later came back with the book she had noticed who-knows-when, and handed it to him. He looked like she had just presented him with the Holy Grail.  The card catalog hadn't included it in possible references.

@Megan
Sorry for your loss.
BEAU, in my opinion, is a bona fide word and used today--or do we say BFF? Also, a name. Think Beau Bridges and, sadly, Beau Biden.

@Barry Ancona 

According to xwstats, people normally solve faster than their rolling average, so it takes a relatively lower percentage of slower solvers for a puzzle to be considered "Hard."

<a href="https://xwstats.com/help" target="_blank">https://xwstats.com/help</a>

@SP

I'll grant you that's a good way of looking at this theme - as a constructor you must especially appreciate such additional levels of complexity a peasant like me won't even notice. 

@The X-Phile

True - it's unrealistic to expect being wowed on Monday.

@D

Or if it didn't make the puzzle more interesting by making it harder - I know you're not a fan of gimmicks, but I am, often, and I enjoy a hard Thursday theme.

One like today's though... Meh - at best.

@Matt
Indeed. I don't live in your part of the world but have family there. Everyone is exhausted beyond words. No one sleeps any more because of the repeated flights to the shelter rooms every night when the alerts go off. Daytimes, people scurry out and scurry home. No one has any idea of what Passover will be like.
Well, you know this and more much better than me.  Hoping you and yours (even the cat) stay safe. Glad that you have a metaphysical refuge here. Let's get puzzling!

@max 

Living in the same city as Emory University has caused EMERY to trip me up a few times, but by now I remember both spellings.

Unfortunately, growing up in the era of duck-and-cover drills made me all too familiar with what an ICBM is.

@Nancy J.

Ever heard the Elvis version?

<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=trB8tgwCawU" target="_blank">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=trB8tgwCawU</a>

@The X-Phile
Before I got a subscription, I would buy books of crosswords and solve them in ink. If I made a mistake, I would simply draw another, darker letter on top of the incorrect one.

The puzzle that changed that was one where the spanner was all rebuses, several letters in each square, spelling out Supercalifragilisticexpialidocious. All the corrections I had to make were really quite atrocious! I solved in pencil from then on.

@Barry Ancona
LOL
Now, Barry, you know you have used this before.  I think there is a limit to how many times a clever joke should be unveiled...

@Barry Ancona,

I like hearing about your stone tablets and your water clock. 

Gen n: “What’s a water clock?”

@Helen Wright

Your post had a very paradoxical twist to it. If your post never posted, then you might have stopped commenting, in which case we would not have known about it and could not have exhorted you to stay. But since it did post, we have no need to exhort you to stay, since you said you would only leave if it didn’t post.
So I’ll say this instead—I’m glad it posted, and I’m glad you are staying.

@Rosa
Just be glad it wasn't MIRV. (Multiple Independently-targeted Re-entry Vehicle.) That would have been a bit much for a Wednesday.

If you had grown up in the Carter years, you would have learned all about ICBMs and ABMs from the SALT II negotiations. And then there was Reagan's SDI. Signs of the times, I guess.

@Mean Old Lady

The "breakfast test"?
I can just barely smell the smoke from the fire when that bridge got burned.

@Eric H. - Better let your northern friends know about this... they're doing it wrong!


<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stag_and_doe" target="_blank">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stag_and_doe</a>

Also: of you really want to get pedantic, the male companion of a hind is a hart, not a stag.

@lucky13,

I believe the companion of a roebuck is called a sears. 

